<Base title="Methodology" tagline="● How the ledger keeps score"
  description="How the prediction ledger registers, scores, and retires claims — the public rules, versioned.">
  <div class="wrap">
    <section class="page-intro">
      <div class="kicker">Methodology · v{version}</div>
      <h1>How the ledger <em>keeps score.</em></h1>
      <p class="deck">The point of the <a class="accent" href="/ledger">prediction ledger</a> is to be checkable. These are the rules it runs by — published so the scoring can be audited and argued with, not taken on trust.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="blk" style="border-bottom:none">
      <div class="prose">
        <h2>1. Registration</h2>
        <p>Every claim enters with a single probability, a written test for what would disconfirm it, a base rate it has to beat where one exists, and a resolve-by date. The probability <b>locks the moment the claim is registered</b> and is never edited afterwards. The registration timestamp is part of the record.</p>
        <h2>2. Two populations, one estimator</h2>
        <p>Claims are attributed to whoever committed them — <b>bruno</b> (my own stated positions) or <b>twin</b> (the system's analyses). The two are scored as <b>separate populations</b> so the machine cannot launder its guesses into my track record, or vice versa.</p>
        <h2>3. Pre-registration audit</h2>
        <p>Before a claim counts, it is checked against the public record for whether the outcome was <i>already known</i> at registration time. A question answered before it was asked is not a forecast — such claims are <b>invalidated</b>, kept visible in full, and excluded from scoring.</p>
        <h2>4. Resolution</h2>
        <p>A claim resolves when its written test is met by public evidence, on or before its deadline. Resolutions record the outcome, the date, and a sourced note. <b>Resolutions are never deleted</b>; misses stay on the board.</p>
        <h2>5. Scoring</h2>
        <p>Resolved, still-valid claims are scored with the <b>Brier score</b> — the squared distance between the locked probability and the realised outcome, <code>(probability − outcome)²</code>. Lower is better; 0.25 is the coin-flip line. Invalidated and withdrawn claims are never scored — the record does not keep wins it did not earn. Calibration is read by population, by confidence, and by horizon, with a standing caveat while the resolved sample is small.</p>
        <h2>6. Corrections</h2>
        <p>When a factual error is found in an evidence note, it is corrected with a dated, append-only correction entry rather than a silent edit. The original and the correction both stay on the record.</p>
        <h2>7. Invalidation &amp; withdrawal</h2>
        <p>A claim can be <b>invalidated</b> (disqualified — e.g. the outcome pre-dated registration) or <b>withdrawn</b>. Both remain publicly visible with their reason, and neither contributes to the score.</p>
        <h2>8. Provenance</h2>
        <p>Everything shown here is a styled view of the machine-readable record in the public <a href="https://github.com/chiKeka/ledger">chiKeka/ledger</a> repository. The site renders nothing the ledger's own renderer did not produce, and each ledger view names the source commit it was built from.</p>
        <hr />
        <p class="mono" style="font-size:12px;color:var(--dim)">Version {version} · last updated {updated}. Changes to these rules are versioned; the scoring of already-registered claims is never changed retroactively.</p>
        <p><a class="btn line" href="/ledger">← Back to the ledger</a></p>
      </div>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>
